مقالاتividual Sonicwall Firewall SSL SettingJul 20, 2021 • sonicwall • firewall • security • sslQuite a few of my clients have asked me about Sonicwall firewall SSL configuration. As Sonicwall TZ series, NSA series, and SRA series devices are commonly used for Edge firewall duties, it's essential to ensure that the SSL settings are set up correctly.

Here’s how to configure Sonicwall firewall SSL settings:

1。Check if SSL Offloading is enabled:
   Once logged in to the Sonicwall firewall, navigate to the "Firewall" menu, and click on "SSL Offloading".
   Ensure that "SSL Offloading for FortiMail" is enabled.
   If it's not enabled, click on "Enable SSL Offloading for FortiMail", and place a checkmark in that box.

2。Configure SSL/TLS settings:
   To configure SSL/TLS settings, go to the "Network" menu, and click on "SSL/TLS Settings".
   Here, you can set SSL/TLS options for:

   a) Web Server:
      - Ensure that "Active" is checked.
      - Enter your domain name in the "Server Domain" field.
      - Choose your certificate type — "Local" (installed on the Sonicwall) or "External" (Remote certificate).
      - If "Local" is selected, upload your SSL certificate and private key into the Sonicwall.
      - If "External" is selected, enter the "Certificate Server FQDN" and the "Private Key Password".

   b) Email Server:
      - Choose your SMTP server type — "Forwarding", "Relay", "Outbound", or "Inbound".
      - Select your email port number — commonly 25, 587, or 465.

   c) Web Server Internal:
      - Set your "Server Domain" to be compatible with your internal DNS.
      - Choose your certificate type — "Local" or "External", and follow the same process described above.

After setting up the SSL settings, you should test them to ensure they are functioning correctly. To do this, you can connect to your Sonicwall using a web browser and test if you can connect to your Sonicwall on HTTPS.

It's critical to keep your SSL settings up-to-date and enabled to protect your network from unauthorized access, eavesdropping, and other cyber threats. Furthermore, as new Certificate Authority (CA) Root CAs get added, ensure to import them into your Sonicwall firewall to avoid any connection issues.
